            <P><a name="contdisc"><font face="Arial" size="2"></font></a><b><font color="#ff0000" face="Arial" size="2">History Of The Internet</font></b>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">From: "<a href="mailto:jere@gte.net">Jere
            Matlock</a>"</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Sorry for the confusion generated by
            my incorrect statement.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2"><i>...where the web was 20 years ago
            - all text, and simple HTML.</i></font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">The "internet" was around
            20 years ago. The "web" wasn't. Although "web"
            and "internet" are used interchangeably these days - they
            are actually two different things. The "World Wide Web"
            being the information presented by linked computers accessible
            through HTTP and formatted primarily using HTML. The
            "internet" was around long before that, originally built
            by DARPA to let our government keep talking to itself in the event
            of nuclear war -- so Defense Department installations could share
            information even if entire cities were wiped off the map, with all
            their infrastructure ruined.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">I was wrong about when HTML was
            invented by Tim Berners-Lee - he decided not to patent it in 1990,
            so one can only assume it was designed and written shortly before
            that - 1989 sounds right. So HTML wasn't around before that. It was
            HTTP and HTML that allowed all the computers to talk to each other,
            finally.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Here is an excerpt from a long
            article in Business Week ( <a href="http://snurl.com/jnp">http://snurl.com/jnp</a>&nbsp;
            ) of March 2002:</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2"><i>Berners-Lee praises the
            contributions of Cailliau and the other co-conspirators in his 1999
            book, Weaving the Web. "Tim's a very modest person, and he has
            been careful to credit the people who've worked with him," says
            Vinton G. Cerf, senior vice-president at WorldCom Inc., who helped
            spawn the Internet in the early 1970s as a medium for scientific
            collaborations.</i></font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">My brother-in-law worked for the
            Defense Department as head of computer systems in a US Navy sub base
            in 1975 - he told me about the network they had and a few of the
            things it could do (what he could tell me without violating national
            security). That was my introduction to the internet, 27 years ago.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">So, while the nucleus of the internet
            WAS around 20 years ago the web (and HTML) was not. I stand (er,
            sit) corrected on my mistakes.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Best,<br>
            <br>
            Jeré Matlock<br>
            <a href="http://www.wordsinarow.com">http://www.wordsinarow.com</a>&nbsp;<br>
            Writing | Website Design & Marketing | SEO</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">[ Moderator comment ]&nbsp;<br>
            And, according to at least one person at the IETF, the Internet has
            just celebrated its 20th birthday: <a href="http://www1.ietf.org/mail-archive/ietf/Current/msg18554.html">http://www1.ietf.org</a>&nbsp;
            January 1, 1983 was the day the ARPANET officially switched from the
            NCP protocol to TCP/IP. ~ Veronica</font></p>

