            <P><font face="Arial" size="2"><b><a name="contdisc4"><font color="#ff0000">
            </font></a><font color="#ff0000"><br>
            </font><font color="#ff0000">Browser Compatibility -- How Far Do You Go?</font></b>

            </font>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">From: <a href="mailto:pwilso15@tampabay.rr.com">Paul
            Wilson</a></font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2"><i>a common mistake that people make
            is in analysing the browser percentages using a particular site.</i>&nbsp;
            - Craig</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Looking at our web site a year ago
            showed a high one week of 8% of customers using a Netscape 4.X
            browser. For the past two months it has been hovering around 1.5% I
            think most people have updated.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">We still support 4.X, but to a lesser
            extent. At some point we will have to stop wasting time and money
            supporting a dead browser. We have not decided when that will be.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">I don't know how many of the 1.5% are
            PC users, Mac users or Linux users. The log software is not that
            sophisticated<i>.</i></font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2"><i>It can be time consuming to test
            all browsers so my advice (if you have a good business case to
            support particular browsers) is:&nbsp;</i> - Craig</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">There is an easy alternative to these
            hassles. Use two stylesheets. It's easier than you think!</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Older legacy browsers do not support
            the @import function which calls in a second style sheet. This means
            you can use TWO style sheets without resorting to JavaScript, PHP or
            other scripts!</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">The second style sheet is simply
            ignored by older legacy browsers.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Here's how you do it: Create your
            first style sheet with a basic body background and ordinary font
            support suitable for Netscape 4.X.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Include the call to the second style
            sheet like this:</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">@import url(secondstyle.css);&nbsp;</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Put your newer unsupported styles (by
            NN 4.X anyway) in the second style sheet. Since newer browsers will
            call this second style sheet, you have better control for these
            viewers.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Your legacy viewers don't get a gray
            background and ugly base fonts. Who says you can't eat your cake and
            have it too? Now you know what "cascading" is good for.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">There are known security problems
            with older browsers. Some of it has to do with Y2K bugs and some of
            it has to do with older algorithms used back then. People need to be
            pushed to update if at all possible.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">I know some companies don't allow
            this but they are creating other problems. If they don't want to
            upgrade I.E. daily, they can go with Opera or a newer Netscape or
            Gecko.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Paul Wilson</font></p>

            <P>
            <a href="mailto:design@adventive.com">
            <FONT face=Arial size=2>
            <img border="0" src="http://www.audettemedia.com/emailtest/images/comment.gif" width="130" height="20">
            </FONT>
            </a>
