            <P>

            <b><font color="#ff0000" face="Arial" size="2"><a name="hello"></a>1st Page 2000</font></b>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">From: "<a href="mailto:netinfo@net500.com">J.
            Leslie Booth</a>"</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Greetings I-Designers ..</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Just a note of caution on
            1stPage2000.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">I found 1stPage2000 back in late 99
            when it first released. Excited that it was an almost exact copy of
            HomeSite, Free and seemed to have a number of really good add-ons, I
            jumped at the chance to try it out. It was GREAT! However, by that
            time I was using Dreamweaver 2.0 and HomeSite 3.0 extensively. But,
            in my job at Purdue University, I test out EVERYTHING .. and I do
            mean EVERYTHING!! ... to see how it works in the academic arena. So
            .. Free and wonderfully smooth .. you bet I just had to use it. And
            use it I did.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">I created and updated over a dozen
            large sites (excess of 500 pages each) and really liked the way it
            worked.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">But then came early 2002 and the
            latest version update at the time! And once again I was the
            recipient of a BIG disappointment!</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">I d had a similar painful occurrence
            early in the WYSIWYG era with Front Page (Microsoft s MAJOR abortion
            of an HTML tool .. Oh, did you get the impression I DON'T use or
            like FP? Well.... you re darned tootin I DO NOT!) . In it s early
            development it was a major piece of crap (PoC).. it s now just a big
            PoC. I lost over 2500 pages of HTML to its code altering effects and
            swore I d never use it again and haven't!</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">So, when I lost 2000+ pages to an
            undetermined internal demon in 1stPage2000 ... I began to wonder if
            it had become the next FP! Oh... the new 1stPage2000, just like
            HomeSite 4.0 HAS a WYSIWYG face; an attempt to look like Dreamweaver
            and HomeSite; you just have to select it over code-only. Needless to
            say, I immediately uninstalled 1stPage2000 and warned all my
            contacts about its potential for lethal effects on HTML or XHTML
            code. I was EXTREMELY disappointed! It had shown such promise. But,
            as one person to whom I bemoaned this frustration said, .. you do
            get what you pay for. Uh, huh! It s true ... regardless of what WANT
            to think.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Now to be fair .. NOT everyone who
            uses the new 1stPage2000 suffers the same effects or any adverse
            effects at all. This was even more startling.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">I had noticed a major negative report
            on the CNET site when I downloaded the new 1stPage2000 in early
            2002, but discounted it as either an inexperienced user or someone
            with a chip . But after I got dumped on, I re-read the comment and
            realized the person was knowledgable... so, I contacted him. Our
            experiences were almost identical ... so were our platforms: Intel
            333 and AMD K2 s. Those who seemed to have little to no problems
            were using faster machines heavy Intel and greater RAM 512+. What
            this has to do with the problems, we never did find out, but they
            were so consistent, there must be a connection: we just don t know
            what it is.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">So .. realize .. 1stPage2000 COULD be
            a dangerous liaison for you. If you choose to use it .. be careful
            and be willing to experience a potential for a big loss in data: it
            IS possible .. and the probability I would say: if you are using the
            same platforms we found to be susceptible - is high, as well.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">Just my $.02 worth ...</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">les</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">.. code, no matter how great it
            works, is NOT GOOD, unless its well documented.</font></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">J. Leslie Booth<br>
            Owner/Cybermediast<br>
            NET500 CG<br>
            </font><a href="http://www.net500.com"><font face="Arial" size="2">www.net500.com</font></a></p>
            <p><font face="Arial" size="2">[ Moderator comment ]&nbsp;<br>
            But we do all have backups of our sites, right?? ~ Veronica</font></p>

